Take your large plastic container and place it under the reaction tank of your biodiesel processor. You may need a few of these containers, depending on the size of the batch of biodiesel. Unhook the hose from the processor. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f8/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f8/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Place it in the plastic container and open the valve on the bottom of the reaction tank. The dark glycerin will run out of the tank and into the container. This is the by-product of your reaction and you want to drain it out until you see the color change from black to amber. At that point, all of the glycerin has been drained and you're ready to transfer the fuel to the wash tank. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e4/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e4/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Replace the bucket underneath the pump with an empty testing jar and open the valve on the pump. Fill the jar with half water and half biodiesel. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ed/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/ed/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Screw on the lid and give it three solid shakes. Set the jar on a flat surface and wait five minutes. While the shake test is not an absolute indicator of your fuel quality, you'll know if it will be an easy wash.{"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8b/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/8b/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

When the solution settles, you will see an intermediate layer called emulsion between the biodiesel and water. The smaller the layer, the easier your wash will be. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b6/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b6/Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Drain-and-Wash-Your-Biodiesel-Step-3Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
